1. Overview

Freeplane is a software designed to help users create mind maps.  It is a tool that helps users organise their thoughts, plans and ideas. 
Target audience for the software are individuals and teams who need a visual representation of information to communicate information or develop them. 
This can include students, project managers, educators, and researchers. The skill level to use freeplane is very low and very user friendly, 
hence suitable and targeted for beginners. Professionals can also try advance features (scripting and extensions) which can give them more freedom 
and areas for manipulation.

2. Installation & Setup

Installing Freeplane directly:
  Visit https://sourceforge.net/projects/freeplane/.
  Download the latest version of Freeplane.
  
    Windows: Double-click the .exe file and follow the installation wizard
    Mac: Open the .dmg file, then drag Freeplane to the Applications folder.
    Linux: Extract the .tar.gz file and follow the installation instructions in the provided README.

Combining Freeplane
  Go to the Repository(https://github.com/freeplane/freeplane).
  Clone repository or download and extract the project as a ZIP File
  Ensure the following software are installed
    Java Development Kit (JDK 17 or later) → Download from Oracle JDK or use OpenJDK.
    Gradle (used for building the project) → Download from Gradle website or use package managers like brew install gradle (Mac) or choco install gradle (Windows).
    Optional: Visual Studio Code (VS Code) → Download from VS Code website. (Can be replace with terminal)
  Open the Project in VS Code or Terminal
  Build freeplane with ‘gradle build’
  Run Freeplane in BIN folder (freeplane.sh for linux, freeplane.jar for window)

